Space-Time Prediction of Bike Share Demand for NYC

Yuhao Jia

November 17, 2022

1. Introduction

Bike share system need to ‘re-balance’ bicycles across the network.Figuring out how to do this is one of the keys to operating a successful system.

Success to predict bike share demand for each station is essential for move bikes to the right place with trucks for the bike share company. This is also the aim of this project.

In this project, we will use time-space predictive modeling to predict the bike share pattern of each hour in New York City and try to address an operations issue for the citi-bike system provided by lyft.

2.3. Import Census Info

As most trips in this data set mainly happened in Jersey City and Manhattan area, census data of this two areas are loaded and bind as “NYCTracts”. And then the bike share data and “NYCTracts” are joined together as “dat_census”.

NYCCensus <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", 
          variables = c("B01003_001", "B19013_001", 
                        "B02001_002", "B08013_001",
                        "B08012_001", "B08301_001", 
                        "B08301_010", "B01002_001"), 
          year = 2020, 
          state = "NY", 
          geometry = TRUE, 
          county=c("New York"),
          output = "wide") %>%
  rename(Total_Pop =  B01003_001E,
         Med_Inc = B19013_001E,
         Med_Age = B01002_001E,
         White_Pop = B02001_002E,
         Travel_Time = B08013_001E,
         Num_Commuters = B08012_001E,
         Means_of_Transport = B08301_001E,
         Total_Public_Trans = B08301_010E) %>%
  select(Total_Pop, Med_Inc, White_Pop, Travel_Time,
         Means_of_Transport, Total_Public_Trans,
         Med_Age,
         GEOID, geometry) %>%
  mutate(Percent_White = White_Pop / Total_Pop,
         Mean_Commute_Time = Travel_Time / Total_Public_Trans,
         Percent_Taking_Public_Trans = Total_Public_Trans / Means_of_Transport)

2.4. Import Weather Data

Import weather data from station New York City (code NYC) using riem_measures. Temperature, preceipitation and wind speed data was downloaded for the study period.

weather.Panel <- 
  riem_measures(station = "NYC", date_start = "2020-05-01", date_end = "2020-05-31") %>%
  dplyr::select(valid, tmpf, p01i, sknt)%>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
    mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
    mutate(week = week(interval60),
           dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>%
    summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
              Precipitation = sum(p01i),
              Wind_Speed = max(sknt)) %>%
    mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))

3.2 Create Space-Time Panel

In this section, a space-time panel for modeling will be created. First a study panel with 34782 rows was created to make sure each unique station and hour/day combo exists in our data set.

study.panel <- 
  expand.grid(interval60=unique(dat_census$interval60), 
              start.station.id = unique(dat_census$start.station.id)) %>%
  left_join(., dat_census %>%
              select(start.station.id, start.station.name, Origin.Tract, from_longitude, from_latitude )%>%
              distinct() %>%
              group_by(start.station.id) %>%
              slice(1))

nrow(study.panel)      
## [1] 34782

Then the full panel was created by summarizing counts by station for each time interval, keep census info and lat/lon information along for joining later to other data. Data was removed for station IDs that are FALSE.

ride.panel <- 
  dat_census %>%
  mutate(Trip_Counter = 1) %>%
  right_join(study.panel) %>% 
  group_by(interval60, start.station.id, start.station.name, Origin.Tract, from_longitude, from_latitude) %>%
  summarize(Trip_Count = sum(Trip_Counter, na.rm=T)) %>%
  left_join(weather.Panel) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is.na(start.station.id) == FALSE) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(is.na(Origin.Tract) == FALSE)
ride.panel <- 
  left_join(ride.panel, Census %>%
              as.data.frame() %>%
              select(-geometry), by = c("Origin.Tract" = "GEOID"))

3.3. Create time lags

Intuitive sense is that the demand right now should be relatively similar to the demand tomorrow at this time, and to the demand an hour from now, but twelve hours from now, we likely expect the opposite in terms of demand.

So lag variables were also created as fixed effects, and correlations in this lags were also calculated and proved strong.

Also, to control for the effects of holidays (May 28 - Memorial Day) that disrupt the expected demand during a given weekend or weekday, some dummy variables were used to indicate temporal proximity to the holiday.

ride.panel <- 
  ride.panel %>% 
  arrange(start.station.id, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,24),
         holiday = ifelse(yday(interval60) == 148,1,0)) %>%
   mutate(day = yday(interval60)) %>%
   mutate(holidayLag = case_when(dplyr::lag(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "PlusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "PlustTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "PlustThreeDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "MinusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "MinusTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "MinusThreeDays"),
         holidayLag = ifelse(is.na(holidayLag) == TRUE, 0, holidayLag))
as.data.frame(ride.panel) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>% 
    summarise_at(vars(starts_with("lag"), "Trip_Count"), mean, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -interval60, -Trip_Count) %>%
    mutate(Variable = factor(Variable, levels=c("lagHour","lag2Hours","lag3Hours","lag4Hours",
                                                "lag12Hours","lag1day")))%>%
    group_by(Variable) %>%  
    summarize(correlation = round(cor(Value, Trip_Count),2))

4. Prediction Models

4.1. Run Models

In this section, data was split into a training and a test set. The training set includes the first 3 weeks of the month and the test set includes the last two.

Using training data, five linear models were created to see how different variables effect the power of the model. The first models include only temporal controls, but the later ones contain all of our lag information.

ride.Train <- filter(ride.panel, week >= 20)
ride.Test <- filter(ride.panel, week < 20)
reg1 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg2 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg3 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg4 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name +  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg5 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours +lag12Hours + lag1day + holidayLag + holiday, 
     data=ride.Train)

4.2. Predict for test data

After finishing runing models, a nested data frame of test data by week was created.

ride.Test.weekNest <- 
  ride.Test %>%
  nest(-week) 
model_pred <- function(dat, fit){
   pred <- predict(fit, newdata = dat)}

Below shows the predicted results summary of all five models both on training set and test set. The last two model have similar and lowest MAE among all models, which indicates that they are better models. And their MAE around 0.53 is a relatively low value considering the number of trips per hour, which means the last two model is pretty good.

week_predictions <- 
  ride.Test.weekNest %>% 
    mutate(ATime_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg1, .f = model_pred),
           BSpace_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg2, .f = model_pred),
           CTime_Space_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg3, .f = model_pred),
           DTime_Space_FE_timeLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg4, .f = model_pred),
           ETime_Space_FE_timeLags_holidayLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg5, .f = model_pred)) %>% 
    gather(Regression, Prediction, -data, -week) %>%
    mutate(Observed = map(data, pull, Trip_Count),
           Absolute_Error = map2(Observed, Prediction,  ~ abs(.x - .y)),
           MAE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, mean, na.rm = TRUE),
           sd_AE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, sd, na.rm = TRUE))

Cross validation analysis was also run to test the power of the model over all. Here, the last model was used under a 100 folds cross validation. The overall accuracy (MAE around 0,7) also shows it’s a generally good model.

fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100)
set.seed(825)

reg.cv <- 
  train(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours +lag12Hours + lag1day + holidayLag + holiday, 
     data=ride.panel, method = "lm", trControl = fitControl, na.action = na.pass)

5. Visualize Accuracy & Generalizability

To further explore the accuracy and generalizability, in this section, they were visualized.

5.1. Examine Error Metrics for Accuracy

The accuracy of 5 models was visualized in the following 2 plots.

5.2. Space-Time Error Evaluation

In this section, the generalizability of the last model was tested through weekdays/weekends, different period of a day, and socio-economic variables.

By plotting observed vs. predicted for different times of day during the week and weekend, it can be seen that the coefficients (red lines) are lower than 1 (black line). This indicates that the model is underpredicting in general but it’s more accurate at weekend overnight.

6 Conclusions

Based on the performance of the model, it is pretty useful for the bike re-balancing plan. For a particular day and a station, the model can be used to predict the demand of trips every hour with error less than 1 trip.

According to the prediction, there will be several high volume periods every day. Before those period, the bike share company can check the status of bike distribution for each station, and move bikes between stations to meet the demand of high volume periods.

Although the model underpredicts the peak, and there might be some spatial process for the error, the model is generally effective. To improve the model, adding spatial lag components or specific spatial process as predictors might be useful.
